WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.892 align:middle line:90%


00:00:05.892 --> 00:00:09.820 align:middle line:90%
[THEME MUSIC]

00:00:09.820 --> 00:00:27.504 align:middle line:90%


00:00:27.504 --> 00:00:29.670 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA MEREDITH: When was
the last time you simply

00:00:29.670 --> 00:00:33.220 align:middle line:10%
sat and listened to music, eyes
closed, the rest of the world

00:00:33.220 --> 00:00:34.590 align:middle line:10%
shut out?

00:00:34.590 --> 00:00:36.550 align:middle line:84%
Today, music is more
used as background

00:00:36.550 --> 00:00:40.730 align:middle line:84%
to a busy, even frantic life,
often adding even more noise.

00:00:40.730 --> 00:00:43.330 align:middle line:84%
Gary Malkin is with us today
to speak about the richness

00:00:43.330 --> 00:00:45.880 align:middle line:84%
and depth our lives take
on when we give sound

00:00:45.880 --> 00:00:46.760 align:middle line:90%
our full attention.

00:00:46.760 --> 00:00:49.800 align:middle line:84%
In fact, even when we don't
give it our full attention,

00:00:49.800 --> 00:00:51.540 align:middle line:84%
because you create
ambient music just

00:00:51.540 --> 00:00:54.110 align:middle line:84%
like background noise
in cafes yourself.

00:00:54.110 --> 00:00:57.490 align:middle line:84%
So Gary, let's start with--
almost your entire life,

00:00:57.490 --> 00:01:00.860 align:middle line:84%
you've been a musician,
but at what point

00:01:00.860 --> 00:01:03.810 align:middle line:84%
did you start realizing
that music could be used

00:01:03.810 --> 00:01:07.170 align:middle line:84%
to aid in healing and alter
states of consciousness

00:01:07.170 --> 00:01:09.066 align:middle line:84%
and-- how did that all
come about for you?

00:01:09.066 --> 00:01:10.690 align:middle line:10%
>>GARY MALKIN: There
are many incidents

00:01:10.690 --> 00:01:12.090 align:middle line:10%
all throughout my
life, but the one

00:01:12.090 --> 00:01:14.520 align:middle line:10%
that I remember that's the
earliest was when I-- you know,

00:01:14.520 --> 00:01:16.490 align:middle line:10%
I started playing
the piano just by ear

00:01:16.490 --> 00:01:18.610 align:middle line:10%
when I was five years old,
and apparently I could

00:01:18.610 --> 00:01:19.890 align:middle line:10%
play anything I could hear.

00:01:19.890 --> 00:01:21.210 align:middle line:90%
I just sat down.

00:01:21.210 --> 00:01:23.168 align:middle line:84%
And I remember that when
there were-- you know,

00:01:23.168 --> 00:01:25.740 align:middle line:84%
I grew up in a typically
dysfunctional Jewish family

00:01:25.740 --> 00:01:28.062 align:middle line:84%
where everybody was, you
know, like Woody Allen movies,

00:01:28.062 --> 00:01:29.520 align:middle line:84%
constantly interrupting
each other.

00:01:29.520 --> 00:01:31.410 align:middle line:84%
And I remembered
that when I was--

00:01:31.410 --> 00:01:34.070 align:middle line:84%
it was just too much for me,
because I was a sensitive kid,

00:01:34.070 --> 00:01:37.130 align:middle line:84%
I'd go to the piano and
create a sanctuary for myself,

00:01:37.130 --> 00:01:39.250 align:middle line:90%
and I'd self-soothe.

00:01:39.250 --> 00:01:41.260 align:middle line:84%
On some level of
my being, I don't

00:01:41.260 --> 00:01:43.200 align:middle line:84%
know if I was aware of
it, but on some level

00:01:43.200 --> 00:01:46.430 align:middle line:84%
I recognized that everything in
the house started chilling out.

00:01:46.430 --> 00:01:48.545 align:middle line:84%
And it was like a
Pavlovian experience, where

00:01:48.545 --> 00:01:50.720 align:middle line:84%
I'd start to play
for my own well-being

00:01:50.720 --> 00:01:52.650 align:middle line:84%
and then all the fights
started to subside

00:01:52.650 --> 00:01:55.290 align:middle line:84%
and people started
getting more centered.

00:01:55.290 --> 00:01:57.330 align:middle line:84%
And I think on
some level I sensed

00:01:57.330 --> 00:01:59.320 align:middle line:84%
that there was a connection
between the music

00:01:59.320 --> 00:02:00.980 align:middle line:90%
and the environment in the home.

00:02:00.980 --> 00:02:03.310 align:middle line:84%
And I think that's when I
started getting hooked to it,

00:02:03.310 --> 00:02:03.620 align:middle line:90%
you know?

00:02:03.620 --> 00:02:04.980 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: That's
interesting, yeah.

00:02:04.980 --> 00:02:06.896 align:middle line:84%
And I wonder how many
people-- I did the same.

00:02:06.896 --> 00:02:09.729 align:middle line:84%
I'd come home from
school, drop the books,

00:02:09.729 --> 00:02:12.390 align:middle line:84%
and start playing the piano,
and just play and play

00:02:12.390 --> 00:02:13.400 align:middle line:90%
until I was calm.

00:02:13.400 --> 00:02:15.274 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: I think it
saved my life, honestly,

00:02:15.274 --> 00:02:17.780 align:middle line:84%
because I had this
experience where

00:02:17.780 --> 00:02:20.050 align:middle line:84%
the experience of
presence wasn't very

00:02:20.050 --> 00:02:22.940 align:middle line:84%
common in this very
dysfunctional-- and loving,

00:02:22.940 --> 00:02:24.480 align:middle line:90%
but very busy family.

00:02:24.480 --> 00:02:25.900 align:middle line:84%
So the idea of
having a place that

00:02:25.900 --> 00:02:28.960 align:middle line:84%
was completely
whole and complete,

00:02:28.960 --> 00:02:32.450 align:middle line:84%
and have a place to just
resonate in the beauty of music

00:02:32.450 --> 00:02:34.052 align:middle line:84%
was just a life-saving
experience.

00:02:34.052 --> 00:02:35.510 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well and
as you said, you

00:02:35.510 --> 00:02:38.690 align:middle line:84%
helped heal the background noise
of your life in that household,

00:02:38.690 --> 00:02:39.490 align:middle line:90%
too.

00:02:39.490 --> 00:02:42.076 align:middle line:84%
Did anyone ever comment on
it when you were growing up?

00:02:42.076 --> 00:02:44.450 align:middle line:84%
Did they like you to play, or
did they find your practice

00:02:44.450 --> 00:02:47.230 align:middle line:84%
annoying or-- how did the rest
of the people in your family

00:02:47.230 --> 00:02:48.152 align:middle line:90%
experience your music?

00:02:48.152 --> 00:02:50.110 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: I didn't grow
up in a musical family.

00:02:50.110 --> 00:02:52.710 align:middle line:84%
And my mother, she was in the
kitchen cooking, and she said,

00:02:52.710 --> 00:02:54.680 align:middle line:84%
Gary, play "Happy
Talk"-- you know,

00:02:54.680 --> 00:02:56.450 align:middle line:84%
a typical Jewish
Brooklyn mother--

00:02:56.450 --> 00:02:59.330 align:middle line:84%
and there was one song she
loved from "South Pacific,"

00:02:59.330 --> 00:03:00.620 align:middle line:90%
and I just thought, oh my god.

00:03:00.620 --> 00:03:03.790 align:middle line:84%
So I knew how to get her really
happy by just playing this one

00:03:03.790 --> 00:03:04.640 align:middle line:90%
song.

00:03:04.640 --> 00:03:06.910 align:middle line:84%
You know, but there was
something, just in response

00:03:06.910 --> 00:03:09.780 align:middle line:84%
to your question, that
was-- fast forward

00:03:09.780 --> 00:03:13.170 align:middle line:84%
to when I was just beginning
my film scoring career,

00:03:13.170 --> 00:03:17.030 align:middle line:84%
and I was watching the audience
on the opening night of a New

00:03:17.030 --> 00:03:19.206 align:middle line:90%
York film festival.

00:03:19.206 --> 00:03:21.480 align:middle line:84%
It was the first
documentary I did

00:03:21.480 --> 00:03:25.540 align:middle line:84%
that was about promoting
anti-nuclear-- an understanding

00:03:25.540 --> 00:03:27.080 align:middle line:84%
of how nuclear
energy was affecting

00:03:27.080 --> 00:03:29.760 align:middle line:84%
our lives in peacetime, and
how it was causing cancer

00:03:29.760 --> 00:03:31.150 align:middle line:90%
from the downwind and all that.

00:03:31.150 --> 00:03:33.000 align:middle line:84%
And I was in the
back of the audience,

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:34.708 align:middle line:84%
and there was this
part of the film where

00:03:34.708 --> 00:03:36.150 align:middle line:90%
it was so filled with despair.

00:03:36.150 --> 00:03:38.191 align:middle line:84%
And people were not
breathing, and you could just

00:03:38.191 --> 00:03:40.850 align:middle line:84%
feel the place thick with
this energy of just like, ugh.

00:03:40.850 --> 00:03:42.540 align:middle line:84%
And then this theme
that I came up

00:03:42.540 --> 00:03:46.720 align:middle line:84%
with that was meant
to communicate hope,

00:03:46.720 --> 00:03:50.410 align:middle line:84%
suddenly this oboe line came
in and I literally almost saw

00:03:50.410 --> 00:03:51.580 align:middle line:90%
the air lift.

00:03:51.580 --> 00:03:53.350 align:middle line:84%
I heard people
breathing more deeply.

00:03:53.350 --> 00:03:55.080 align:middle line:90%
I was about 28 years old.

00:03:55.080 --> 00:04:00.250 align:middle line:84%
And that was the moment to
me, as beginning my career,

00:04:00.250 --> 00:04:03.250 align:middle line:84%
that I went, oh my god, this
is so much more than just

00:04:03.250 --> 00:04:04.550 align:middle line:90%
entertainment or show business.

00:04:04.550 --> 00:04:05.550 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Absolutely.

00:04:05.550 --> 00:04:07.150 align:middle line:90%
It drives the emotions.

00:04:07.150 --> 00:04:11.480 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I think that's what
isn't particularly well

00:04:11.480 --> 00:04:15.290 align:middle line:84%
understood a lot of times
in production in general,

00:04:15.290 --> 00:04:16.790 align:middle line:90%
is how important the music is.

00:04:16.790 --> 00:04:18.800 align:middle line:84%
And I used to produce
documentaries and lots

00:04:18.800 --> 00:04:22.300 align:middle line:84%
of other shows, and for
me it was always backward.

00:04:22.300 --> 00:04:26.630 align:middle line:84%
Usually, the musical
score is added last.

00:04:26.630 --> 00:04:30.440 align:middle line:84%
And to me, I had to hear
the sound of the music that

00:04:30.440 --> 00:04:32.830 align:middle line:84%
was going to accompany
the story before I ever

00:04:32.830 --> 00:04:35.090 align:middle line:84%
saw the real story
or even the imagery--

00:04:35.090 --> 00:04:35.890 align:middle line:90%
>>MALKIN: Yeah.

00:04:35.890 --> 00:04:38.580 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: --because people
live in their emotions

00:04:38.580 --> 00:04:41.020 align:middle line:84%
when they're watching
these, and the music is

00:04:41.020 --> 00:04:42.130 align:middle line:90%
what drives the emotions.

00:04:42.130 --> 00:04:42.570 align:middle line:90%
>>MALKIN: Totally.

00:04:42.570 --> 00:04:45.390 align:middle line:84%
Well, and music is the universal
language of the heart, right?

00:04:45.390 --> 00:04:45.880 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Absolutely.

00:04:45.880 --> 00:04:47.270 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: So if
you-- that says a lot

00:04:47.270 --> 00:04:48.686 align:middle line:84%
about your emotional
intelligence,

00:04:48.686 --> 00:04:51.700 align:middle line:84%
because if you don't have a
bottom-line grounder of what

00:04:51.700 --> 00:04:53.620 align:middle line:84%
it is emotionally
that you're feeling,

00:04:53.620 --> 00:04:56.644 align:middle line:84%
everything else is all just
noise and separate parts.

00:04:56.644 --> 00:04:58.060 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well and
in a story, you

00:04:58.060 --> 00:05:00.775 align:middle line:84%
want to know the emotional
message that's being delivered.

00:05:00.775 --> 00:05:02.150 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: That's
the bottom line.

00:05:02.150 --> 00:05:03.110 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: You have
to be clear on it.

00:05:03.110 --> 00:05:03.290 align:middle line:90%
>>MALKIN: Right.

00:05:03.290 --> 00:05:05.220 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And music is
what takes people to it.

00:05:05.220 --> 00:05:06.080 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: It's
amazing, isn't it?

00:05:06.080 --> 00:05:07.038 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: It really is.

00:05:07.038 --> 00:05:09.710 align:middle line:84%
So amidst all of this, you
ultimately saw yourself--

00:05:09.710 --> 00:05:12.790 align:middle line:84%
and as you explain
yourself to be,

00:05:12.790 --> 00:05:16.860 align:middle line:84%
it's a different kind of-- a
music and health innovator.

00:05:16.860 --> 00:05:18.940 align:middle line:84%
Not a sound healer,
which I was kind

00:05:18.940 --> 00:05:20.780 align:middle line:90%
of erroneously calling you.

00:05:20.780 --> 00:05:23.240 align:middle line:90%
Tell us what that means.

00:05:23.240 --> 00:05:25.910 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: Well you know, we're
experiencing a renaissance

00:05:25.910 --> 00:05:28.250 align:middle line:84%
of quantification, you
know, proof everywhere

00:05:28.250 --> 00:05:30.630 align:middle line:84%
around the power of
music and sound healing.

00:05:30.630 --> 00:05:32.530 align:middle line:84%
And right now, there's
a great leveling

00:05:32.530 --> 00:05:34.490 align:middle line:84%
in the great tent
of sound and music,

00:05:34.490 --> 00:05:37.280 align:middle line:84%
because with neurological
studies and all this stuff,

00:05:37.280 --> 00:05:39.730 align:middle line:84%
we're actually seeing what
happens to our bodies,

00:05:39.730 --> 00:05:43.580 align:middle line:84%
our minds, our
biological systems, when

00:05:43.580 --> 00:05:45.840 align:middle line:84%
we expose ourselves to
that kind of listening

00:05:45.840 --> 00:05:48.280 align:middle line:90%
and those kinds of sounds.

00:05:48.280 --> 00:05:51.210 align:middle line:84%
So I back-doored into
this through the power

00:05:51.210 --> 00:05:52.010 align:middle line:90%
of film music.

00:05:52.010 --> 00:05:54.020 align:middle line:84%
You know, I was-- I wanted
to be John Williams.

00:05:54.020 --> 00:05:55.728 align:middle line:84%
You know, I wanted to
be a film composer.

00:05:55.728 --> 00:05:59.380 align:middle line:84%
So my way into understanding
how human beings are affected

00:05:59.380 --> 00:06:04.390 align:middle line:84%
by music came through 25 years
of scoring television and film

00:06:04.390 --> 00:06:05.190 align:middle line:90%
and commercials.

00:06:05.190 --> 00:06:08.270 align:middle line:84%
And I had a television show
called "Unsolved Mysteries"

00:06:08.270 --> 00:06:10.010 align:middle line:84%
that I scored for
15 years, which

00:06:10.010 --> 00:06:12.135 align:middle line:84%
was enough to drive me
crazy, but it was wonderful.

00:06:12.135 --> 00:06:13.310 align:middle line:90%
It was a great team.

00:06:13.310 --> 00:06:13.620 align:middle line:90%
And--

00:06:13.620 --> 00:06:15.661 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well, and that's
a very specific genre,

00:06:15.661 --> 00:06:18.302 align:middle line:84%
creating very specific
emotional responses.

00:06:18.302 --> 00:06:20.010 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: Well yeah,
it was happy and sad

00:06:20.010 --> 00:06:21.250 align:middle line:90%
and everything in between.

00:06:21.250 --> 00:06:25.760 align:middle line:84%
But when I started to really
explore the idea of-- well,

00:06:25.760 --> 00:06:28.500 align:middle line:84%
it was really out of
my own need for healing

00:06:28.500 --> 00:06:31.540 align:middle line:84%
when a major loss
in my life happened.

00:06:31.540 --> 00:06:34.260 align:middle line:84%
I actually was drawn
to that, like how can I

00:06:34.260 --> 00:06:36.580 align:middle line:84%
create the soundtrack
for my life

00:06:36.580 --> 00:06:40.160 align:middle line:84%
at this point when loss has
hit me in a debilitating way.

00:06:40.160 --> 00:06:43.110 align:middle line:84%
And that's when I
was drawn to create

00:06:43.110 --> 00:06:44.910 align:middle line:84%
this product with
Michael Stillwater called

00:06:44.910 --> 00:06:46.260 align:middle line:90%
"Graceful Passages."

00:06:46.260 --> 00:06:49.570 align:middle line:84%
And what it was was
taking spoken messages

00:06:49.570 --> 00:06:52.810 align:middle line:84%
around loss and
around transitions

00:06:52.810 --> 00:06:54.880 align:middle line:84%
and scoring it in
a way that enables

00:06:54.880 --> 00:06:58.540 align:middle line:84%
us to hear when we're so wigged
out by loss that we actually

00:06:58.540 --> 00:07:01.116 align:middle line:84%
can't even hear words anymore
without that score that you

00:07:01.116 --> 00:07:02.240 align:middle line:90%
were talking about, right--

00:07:02.240 --> 00:07:02.510 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Mm-hm.

00:07:02.510 --> 00:07:04.140 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: --working
on documentaries.

00:07:04.140 --> 00:07:09.530 align:middle line:84%
So I came through this process
as a film composer looking

00:07:09.530 --> 00:07:14.940 align:middle line:84%
at how profound it is to receive
wisdom with film score music,

00:07:14.940 --> 00:07:18.640 align:middle line:84%
and how biologically,
physiologically, spiritually,

00:07:18.640 --> 00:07:20.810 align:middle line:84%
emotionally things
change in our ability

00:07:20.810 --> 00:07:23.550 align:middle line:84%
to be present in the
moment, to be engaged

00:07:23.550 --> 00:07:26.730 align:middle line:84%
with our relationships, to
meet our transitions with more

00:07:26.730 --> 00:07:28.120 align:middle line:90%
consciousness, you know?

00:07:28.120 --> 00:07:31.860 align:middle line:84%
So over the launch of this thing
called "Graceful Passages,"

00:07:31.860 --> 00:07:36.110 align:middle line:84%
which was about 15
years ago, I started

00:07:36.110 --> 00:07:39.180 align:middle line:84%
to explore, well,
my god, if music

00:07:39.180 --> 00:07:43.830 align:middle line:84%
can be the digestive enzyme
that allows us to process

00:07:43.830 --> 00:07:45.205 align:middle line:90%
the main course of life--

00:07:45.205 --> 00:07:46.080 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Absolutely.

00:07:46.080 --> 00:07:47.621 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: --if it
can actually enable

00:07:47.621 --> 00:07:49.120 align:middle line:84%
us to assimilate
the meaning when

00:07:49.120 --> 00:07:52.120 align:middle line:84%
we're lost in new
transitions-- birth, death,

00:07:52.120 --> 00:07:54.370 align:middle line:84%
and everything in between--
you know, as they say,

00:07:54.370 --> 00:07:56.760 align:middle line:84%
you know, what is it--
pain is inevitable,

00:07:56.760 --> 00:07:58.340 align:middle line:84%
but suffering is
optional, right?

00:07:58.340 --> 00:07:58.620 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Mm-hm.

00:07:58.620 --> 00:08:00.828 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: If there's a way
to alleviate the suffering

00:08:00.828 --> 00:08:03.540 align:middle line:84%
by assimilating it with
music, by understanding it

00:08:03.540 --> 00:08:06.710 align:middle line:84%
with your heart before
you even-- your mind does,

00:08:06.710 --> 00:08:08.250 align:middle line:90%
what else can it do?

00:08:08.250 --> 00:08:10.470 align:middle line:84%
So that's when I started
to look at the greatest

00:08:10.470 --> 00:08:12.100 align:middle line:90%
challenges in our life.

00:08:12.100 --> 00:08:14.160 align:middle line:90%
How we prepare for birth?

00:08:14.160 --> 00:08:15.190 align:middle line:90%
How we go through birth?

00:08:15.190 --> 00:08:17.800 align:middle line:84%
You know, the pregnancy
issues, the bonding issues.

00:08:17.800 --> 00:08:20.100 align:middle line:84%
How do we deal with
burnout with caregivers?

00:08:20.100 --> 00:08:21.990 align:middle line:84%
How do we face the
3:00 AM moments

00:08:21.990 --> 00:08:24.400 align:middle line:84%
when you're waiting for a
diagnosis with a cancer--

00:08:24.400 --> 00:08:25.920 align:middle line:84%
when you're worried
about cancer?

00:08:25.920 --> 00:08:27.420 align:middle line:84%
How do you deal
with the end of life

00:08:27.420 --> 00:08:29.690 align:middle line:84%
when somebody is giving
you a terminal diagnosis?

00:08:29.690 --> 00:08:31.310 align:middle line:84%
These are these
bottleneck moments

00:08:31.310 --> 00:08:34.020 align:middle line:84%
that you notice in films
have very particular film

00:08:34.020 --> 00:08:36.440 align:middle line:84%
scores to make you feel
very particular things.

00:08:36.440 --> 00:08:37.240 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Mm-hm.

00:08:37.240 --> 00:08:39.980 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: Well, what if
life is so complicated

00:08:39.980 --> 00:08:43.409 align:middle line:84%
now that we need a
private film score

00:08:43.409 --> 00:08:45.100 align:middle line:84%
