00:24:48.150 --> 00:24:49.460 align:middle line:90%
and composition.

00:24:49.460 --> 00:24:52.350 align:middle line:84%
And I was intuitively
drawn to how

00:24:52.350 --> 00:24:56.070 align:middle line:84%
the musics of different
cultures expanded my awareness.

00:24:56.070 --> 00:24:59.330 align:middle line:84%
What I now know is that, when
you actually subject yourself

00:24:59.330 --> 00:25:02.120 align:middle line:84%
to music that you're
not familiar with,

00:25:02.120 --> 00:25:03.840 align:middle line:84%
you can actually
expand your ability

00:25:03.840 --> 00:25:06.820 align:middle line:84%
to relate to other, to
the things that are not

00:25:06.820 --> 00:25:10.660 align:middle line:84%
familiar to you, in a way that's
transferable so that you're

00:25:10.660 --> 00:25:13.955 align:middle line:84%
more accepting and more
resilient to expose yourself

00:25:13.955 --> 00:25:16.330 align:middle line:84%
to things that are different
than you, which is something

00:25:16.330 --> 00:25:18.190 align:middle line:84%
we really need in
this culture today

00:25:18.190 --> 00:25:20.110 align:middle line:84%
based on all the fear
of differences, right.

00:25:20.110 --> 00:25:21.460 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Xenophobia
is a word that's

00:25:21.460 --> 00:25:22.830 align:middle line:90%
popping up all over the planet.

00:25:22.830 --> 00:25:23.530 align:middle line:90%
>>MALKIN: Exactly, right?

00:25:23.530 --> 00:25:23.730 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:25:23.730 --> 00:25:25.970 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: So that level
is one of the basic levels

00:25:25.970 --> 00:25:28.310 align:middle line:84%
I love about exposing
yourself to different musics

00:25:28.310 --> 00:25:29.180 align:middle line:90%
of the world.

00:25:29.180 --> 00:25:32.220 align:middle line:84%
Brings you-- makes you embrace
the human range of experience,

00:25:32.220 --> 00:25:33.020 align:middle line:90%
right?

00:25:33.020 --> 00:25:36.060 align:middle line:84%
And through-- I call the
ethnic music of a culture

00:25:36.060 --> 00:25:40.840 align:middle line:84%
the hieroglyphic thumbprint
of a culture's soul, right.

00:25:40.840 --> 00:25:42.930 align:middle line:84%
But on the level that
you're talking about,

00:25:42.930 --> 00:25:45.360 align:middle line:84%
there are definite
emotions that are not

00:25:45.360 --> 00:25:47.120 align:middle line:90%
correlative in all the cultures.

00:25:47.120 --> 00:25:50.340 align:middle line:84%
I went to-- I'm a big lover
of the Balinese culture.

00:25:50.340 --> 00:25:52.500 align:middle line:84%
And I was in a
gamelan and all that,

00:25:52.500 --> 00:25:55.120 align:middle line:90%
which is a Balinese orchestra.

00:25:55.120 --> 00:25:56.990 align:middle line:84%
But be careful
what you wish for.

00:25:56.990 --> 00:25:58.630 align:middle line:84%
During my honeymoon,
my wife and I

00:25:58.630 --> 00:26:01.840 align:middle line:84%
got stuck for seven or eight
hours in one of these gamelan

00:26:01.840 --> 00:26:05.362 align:middle line:84%
competitions, and we wanted
to kill ourselves after that.

00:26:05.362 --> 00:26:07.895 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Yeah, it maybe
wasn't your vibe, necessarily,

00:26:07.895 --> 00:26:08.770 align:middle line:90%
your frequency range.

00:26:08.770 --> 00:26:10.830 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: Well, it was--
We were-- Yeah, yeah.

00:26:10.830 --> 00:26:12.050 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: But let's
talk about that.

00:26:12.050 --> 00:26:13.130 align:middle line:90%
What is it?

00:26:13.130 --> 00:26:14.005 align:middle line:90%
What is that happens?

00:26:14.005 --> 00:26:16.150 align:middle line:84%
I mean, if you can even
boil it down to something

00:26:16.150 --> 00:26:19.100 align:middle line:84%
as simple as major or
minor, or certain dominance

00:26:19.100 --> 00:26:22.250 align:middle line:84%
of certain type-- certain
chords in certain cultures.

00:26:22.250 --> 00:26:25.840 align:middle line:84%
I mean, when we often-- again,
if an American is listening,

00:26:25.840 --> 00:26:27.000 align:middle line:90%
we can use John Williams.

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:28.750 align:middle line:84%
You brought him up
earlier as an example.

00:26:28.750 --> 00:26:32.100 align:middle line:84%
Everybody resonates pretty much
with John Williams's music,

00:26:32.100 --> 00:26:34.530 align:middle line:84%
which is why he's, what, the
most famous scorer of films

00:26:34.530 --> 00:26:35.120 align:middle line:90%
in America?

00:26:35.120 --> 00:26:36.185 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: Well but
you know, I'm going

00:26:36.185 --> 00:26:36.720 align:middle line:90%
to say something about this.

00:26:36.720 --> 00:26:38.761 align:middle line:84%
One of the reasons I love
John Williams, and also

00:26:38.761 --> 00:26:40.497 align:middle line:84%
Thomas Newman and
Ennio Morricone,

00:26:40.497 --> 00:26:42.080 align:middle line:84%
these are the masters
of the film art.

00:26:42.080 --> 00:26:43.759 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And then
there's Philip Glass.

00:26:43.759 --> 00:26:45.050 align:middle line:90%
>>MALKIN: That's another genre.

00:26:45.050 --> 00:26:45.460 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: A different deal.

00:26:45.460 --> 00:26:45.760 align:middle line:90%
A different genre.

00:26:45.760 --> 00:26:47.060 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: I mean, he's
crossed over into movies.

00:26:47.060 --> 00:26:47.130 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:26:47.130 --> 00:26:48.546 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: But one
of the reasons I

00:26:48.546 --> 00:26:52.064 align:middle line:84%
love these composers
is, metaphorically,

00:26:52.064 --> 00:26:53.480 align:middle line:84%
who these composers--
what they've

00:26:53.480 --> 00:26:55.640 align:middle line:84%
done since Max
Steiner in the '30s

00:26:55.640 --> 00:27:00.510 align:middle line:84%
is that they've been mapping
the musical emotional genome.

00:27:00.510 --> 00:27:01.310 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:27:01.310 --> 00:27:02.110 align:middle line:90%
>>MALKIN: Right?

00:27:02.110 --> 00:27:05.080 align:middle line:84%
In other words, what chords,
what genres, what timbres,

00:27:05.080 --> 00:27:08.360 align:middle line:84%
what rhythms, what
melodies, what textures

00:27:08.360 --> 00:27:11.390 align:middle line:84%
map to the emotional range
of the human experience.

00:27:11.390 --> 00:27:13.170 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: To drive
us toward that end.

00:27:13.170 --> 00:27:13.660 align:middle line:90%
>>MALKIN: Right.

00:27:13.660 --> 00:27:14.460 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:27:14.460 --> 00:27:16.720 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: And they've mastered
it almost to the point

00:27:16.720 --> 00:27:19.290 align:middle line:84%
where they're almost
influencing other cultures.

00:27:19.290 --> 00:27:20.790 align:middle line:84%
So now it's almost
become universal,

00:27:20.790 --> 00:27:23.140 align:middle line:84%
because what is the
largest export of America?

00:27:23.140 --> 00:27:23.940 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:27:23.940 --> 00:27:24.275 align:middle line:90%
Entertainment.

00:27:24.275 --> 00:27:25.470 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: The media
business, right?

00:27:25.470 --> 00:27:25.910 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:27:25.910 --> 00:27:26.680 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: The films
and everything,

00:27:26.680 --> 00:27:28.420 align:middle line:84%
black marketed
everywhere no matter even

00:27:28.420 --> 00:27:29.670 align:middle line:90%
if you're in Papua New Guinea.

00:27:29.670 --> 00:27:32.040 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Oh, yeah, I've picked
them up for $1 in Chiang Mai.

00:27:32.040 --> 00:27:33.140 align:middle line:90%
>>MALKIN: Exactly, right?

00:27:33.140 --> 00:27:34.420 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Laying down
in someone's truck.

00:27:34.420 --> 00:27:35.220 align:middle line:90%
>>MALKIN: Right.

00:27:35.220 --> 00:27:38.390 align:middle line:84%
So I think that there's
way much that we

00:27:38.390 --> 00:27:40.160 align:middle line:90%
don't understand about this.

00:27:40.160 --> 00:27:43.120 align:middle line:84%
But I do think that there's--
if you would talk about major

00:27:43.120 --> 00:27:46.490 align:middle line:84%
and minor, those are the primary
colors of the experience.

00:27:46.490 --> 00:27:48.810 align:middle line:84%
They're very obvious--
not to disparage

00:27:48.810 --> 00:27:50.870 align:middle line:84%
it-- the very obvious
primary colors

00:27:50.870 --> 00:27:52.400 align:middle line:90%
of the distinctions of music.

00:27:52.400 --> 00:27:53.200 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:27:53.200 --> 00:27:55.945 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: And the modes and
the Greek modes in early

00:27:55.945 --> 00:27:59.820 align:middle line:84%
Pythagorean time of talking
about the powers and energetics

00:27:59.820 --> 00:28:00.620 align:middle line:90%
of each mode--

00:28:00.620 --> 00:28:00.890 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:28:00.890 --> 00:28:03.380 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: There were like,
you know, seven modes, right?

00:28:03.380 --> 00:28:06.460 align:middle line:84%
But in the Indian
raga system, there

00:28:06.460 --> 00:28:09.890 align:middle line:84%
are 5,000 ragas, which
is another form of mode,

00:28:09.890 --> 00:28:10.690 align:middle line:90%
if you will.

00:28:10.690 --> 00:28:12.750 align:middle line:84%
And every one of those
ragas was designed

00:28:12.750 --> 00:28:15.850 align:middle line:84%
to create a certain
effect in the human being.

00:28:15.850 --> 00:28:18.850 align:middle line:84%
But it also-- they
had-- I studied with Ali

00:28:18.850 --> 00:28:21.000 align:middle line:84%
Akbar Khan, Indian
classical music,

00:28:21.000 --> 00:28:23.720 align:middle line:84%
when I was-- took my leave
of absence from Oberlin.

00:28:23.720 --> 00:28:27.990 align:middle line:84%
So I've had a lot-- my passion
in my film composing career

00:28:27.990 --> 00:28:30.410 align:middle line:84%
has been about integrating
music from different cultures,

00:28:30.410 --> 00:28:31.770 align:middle line:90%
and authentically so.

00:28:31.770 --> 00:28:33.670 align:middle line:84%
Not giving lip service
to it, if you will.

00:28:33.670 --> 00:28:34.670 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: So let's get--

00:28:34.670 --> 00:28:36.140 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: So those
distinctions, just to finish--

00:28:36.140 --> 00:28:36.940 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:28:36.940 --> 00:28:38.750 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: Those
distinctions are yet

00:28:38.750 --> 00:28:41.330 align:middle line:84%
to be fully understood
on why they work.

00:28:41.330 --> 00:28:44.812 align:middle line:84%
But I think they come down to
what the realm of intervals.

00:28:44.812 --> 00:28:46.520 align:middle line:84%
And many people who
don't know what music

00:28:46.520 --> 00:28:51.460 align:middle line:84%
is, the interval is the
actual vibrational frequency

00:28:51.460 --> 00:28:52.830 align:middle line:90%
between one note and another.

00:28:52.830 --> 00:28:53.630 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Mm-hm.

00:28:53.630 --> 00:28:57.470 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: And when Pythagoras
and Pythagorean tuning created

00:28:57.470 --> 00:29:00.510 align:middle line:84%
it through the music of the
spheres, through mathematics,

00:29:00.510 --> 00:29:06.500 align:middle line:84%
they noticed that it actually
occurs in nature, the pi ratio

00:29:06.500 --> 00:29:08.610 align:middle line:84%
Fibonacci sequence,
these are all Pythagorean

00:29:08.610 --> 00:29:09.930 align:middle line:90%
sacred geometric things.

00:29:09.930 --> 00:29:12.560 align:middle line:84%
Well, they correspond
to sounds, right?

00:29:12.560 --> 00:29:16.050 align:middle line:84%
And you can alter those
sounds in a way that

00:29:16.050 --> 00:29:18.770 align:middle line:84%
effects the human body,
mind, heart, spirit,

00:29:18.770 --> 00:29:21.130 align:middle line:84%
and soul in very unique
ways that we're just

00:29:21.130 --> 00:29:23.250 align:middle line:90%
beginning to understand.

00:29:23.250 --> 00:29:24.220 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes, and--

00:29:24.220 --> 00:29:24.900 align:middle line:90%
>>MALKIN: It's a heady topic.

00:29:24.900 --> 00:29:25.690 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: It is a heady topic.

00:29:25.690 --> 00:29:27.950 align:middle line:84%
And I'm just going to go
back and have you speculate.

00:29:27.950 --> 00:29:29.700 align:middle line:84%
I mean, having
spent time in Asia,

00:29:29.700 --> 00:29:33.260 align:middle line:84%
having spent time in the Middle
East and India, and America,

00:29:33.260 --> 00:29:35.880 align:middle line:84%
for example, whatever it is
that John Williams is appealing

00:29:35.880 --> 00:29:39.940 align:middle line:84%
to in his music to the Western
emotional structure, what

00:29:39.940 --> 00:29:43.900 align:middle line:84%
is happening more in the
Eastern emotional structure

00:29:43.900 --> 00:29:45.190 align:middle line:90%
with the music there?

00:29:45.190 --> 00:29:47.800 align:middle line:84%
Totally different instruments,
different intervals.

00:29:47.800 --> 00:29:48.600 align:middle line:90%
>>MALKIN: Well--

00:29:48.600 --> 00:29:50.840 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: I can't-- I don't
know-- I don't-- you--

00:29:50.840 --> 00:29:51.640 align:middle line:90%
>>MALKIN: Yeah.

00:29:51.640 --> 00:29:53.348 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: I don't even
have the language,

00:29:53.348 --> 00:29:55.760 align:middle line:84%
except that I know I
feel very differently

00:29:55.760 --> 00:29:58.210 align:middle line:84%
and it's not-- I don't
feel as coherent.

00:29:58.210 --> 00:29:59.010 align:middle line:90%
>>MALKIN: Or--

00:29:59.010 --> 00:29:59.530 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Personally.

00:29:59.530 --> 00:30:00.740 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: But here's
the beautiful thing--

00:30:00.740 --> 00:30:02.180 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Not that
that's a bad thing.

00:30:02.180 --> 00:30:02.780 align:middle line:90%
It might be pushing me.

00:30:02.780 --> 00:30:04.680 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: I love-- I
love that you said that,

00:30:04.680 --> 00:30:06.870 align:middle line:84%
because this is the distinction
that I want to make.

00:30:06.870 --> 00:30:09.140 align:middle line:84%
I don't think the word
coherent is an accurate one

00:30:09.140 --> 00:30:10.490 align:middle line:90%
to describe what you're saying.

00:30:10.490 --> 00:30:11.020 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK, what is?

00:30:11.020 --> 00:30:12.990 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: This is why I
said that sometimes exposing

00:30:12.990 --> 00:30:14.880 align:middle line:84%
yourself to things that
are not comfortable--

00:30:14.880 --> 00:30:15.510 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah, yeah.

00:30:15.510 --> 00:30:16.926 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: --or
familiar, sometimes

00:30:16.926 --> 00:30:19.810 align:middle line:84%
are simply because they're
not the neuronal pathways,

00:30:19.810 --> 00:30:20.810 align:middle line:90%
for those of-- you know.

00:30:20.810 --> 00:30:21.520 align:middle line:90%
Do I need to explain that?

00:30:21.520 --> 00:30:21.940 align:middle line:90%
You know that.

00:30:21.940 --> 00:30:22.460 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: No.

00:30:22.460 --> 00:30:23.000 align:middle line:90%
>>MALKIN: Certainly not to you.

00:30:23.000 --> 00:30:24.500 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: You don't
need to explain.

00:30:24.500 --> 00:30:27.050 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: Our neuronal pathways
are used to certain sounds.

00:30:27.050 --> 00:30:28.822 align:middle line:84%
And getting over
the unfamiliar--

00:30:28.822 --> 00:30:31.030 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And certain cadences
and all of that, yeah.

00:30:31.030 --> 00:30:33.572 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: --can be an uplifting
and expanding experience that

00:30:33.572 --> 00:30:34.780 align:middle line:90%
might not be about coherence.

00:30:34.780 --> 00:30:36.200 align:middle line:90%
It might be about unfamiliarity.

00:30:36.200 --> 00:30:37.000 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah--

00:30:37.000 --> 00:30:37.800 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: Discomfort
with the unfamiliar.

00:30:37.800 --> 00:30:39.060 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And I think we
all have this, where--

00:30:39.060 --> 00:30:39.190 align:middle line:90%
>>MALKIN: Of course.

00:30:39.190 --> 00:30:41.189 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: I listen to
mostly world music, right,

00:30:41.189 --> 00:30:45.260 align:middle line:84%
so I'm-- a cross blend of
music from around the planet,

00:30:45.260 --> 00:30:48.130 align:middle line:84%
but there are still certain
sounds that I just don't--

00:30:48.130 --> 00:30:48.930 align:middle line:90%
>>MALKIN: Right.

00:30:48.930 --> 00:30:49.340 align:middle line:90%
Well, I mean--

00:30:49.340 --> 00:30:50.560 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: They
don't do it for me.

00:30:50.560 --> 00:30:51.090 align:middle line:90%
They don't take me anywhere.

00:30:51.090 --> 00:30:53.006 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: Arabic music
has like a half, like--

00:30:53.006 --> 00:30:55.914 align:middle line:90%
[SINGING] da-da-da-da-da-da.

00:30:55.914 --> 00:30:57.580 align:middle line:84%
It's a little less
than the minor third.

00:30:57.580 --> 00:30:57.950 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:30:57.950 --> 00:30:58.070 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:30:58.070 --> 00:30:59.990 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: And at first when
I heard it, it was like,

00:30:59.990 --> 00:31:00.790 align:middle line:90%
you know.

00:31:00.790 --> 00:31:02.876 align:middle line:84%
And in Indian music,
south India has many,

00:31:02.876 --> 00:31:04.500 align:middle line:84%
many different what
they call shruti's.

00:31:04.500 --> 00:31:06.955 align:middle line:90%
[SINGING] da-da-da.

00:31:06.955 --> 00:31:07.755 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Mm-hm.

00:31:07.755 --> 00:31:08.300 align:middle line:90%
Right, right, right.

00:31:08.300 --> 00:31:08.990 align:middle line:90%
>>MALKIN: Sliding through.

00:31:08.990 --> 00:31:09.080 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:31:09.080 --> 00:31:10.410 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: And I was
singing Indian music,

00:31:10.410 --> 00:31:11.660 align:middle line:90%
and I still do to some degree.

00:31:11.660 --> 00:31:13.770 align:middle line:90%
It's a great passion of mine.

00:31:13.770 --> 00:31:16.450 align:middle line:84%
So I love this topic,
and I think that it's

00:31:16.450 --> 00:31:18.070 align:middle line:90%
worth great-- more inquiry.

00:31:18.070 --> 00:31:21.683 align:middle line:84%
But I'll do one major
bold comment about it.

00:31:21.683 --> 00:31:22.550 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:31:22.550 --> 00:31:24.700 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: The East
has been a place that

00:31:24.700 --> 00:31:27.980 align:middle line:84%
has preserved more of what we
would call monophonic music,

00:31:27.980 --> 00:31:31.806 align:middle line:84%
or where the note is more--
the music's more horizontal.

00:31:31.806 --> 00:31:34.030 align:middle line:84%
In other words, there's
a drone underneath--

00:31:34.030 --> 00:31:34.370 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:31:34.370 --> 00:31:34.945 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: --and
there's a melody--

00:31:34.945 --> 00:31:35.210 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:31:35.210 --> 00:31:37.470 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: --that weaves over the
tapestry of the drone, right?

00:31:37.470 --> 00:31:38.290 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Uh-huh.

00:31:38.290 --> 00:31:40.040 align:middle line:90%
>>MALKIN: That's one note.

00:31:40.040 --> 00:31:42.960 align:middle line:84%
Ever since Palestrina
and Telemann and Bach,

00:31:42.960 --> 00:31:46.010 align:middle line:84%
that's polyphonic, and that
has sometimes-- has harmonies.

00:31:46.010 --> 00:31:46.810 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:31:46.810 --> 00:31:47.460 align:middle line:90%
>>MALKIN: Counterpoint.

00:31:47.460 --> 00:31:48.260 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:31:48.260 --> 00:31:50.750 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: Five melodies
happening at once in a fugue.

00:31:50.750 --> 00:31:52.420 align:middle line:84%
And that's a
fundamental difference.

00:31:52.420 --> 00:31:56.160 align:middle line:84%
And I actually think-- this is
why one of my newest project

00:31:56.160 --> 00:31:58.890 align:middle line:84%
is called "Divine 9
Tuning," "Divine 9 Music."

00:31:58.890 --> 00:32:01.810 align:middle line:84%
It's a new tuning system
that's come out of Amsterdam.

00:32:01.810 --> 00:32:05.859 align:middle line:84%
And my newest product is going
to be called "All is Well."

00:32:05.859 --> 00:32:07.400 align:middle line:84%
And the music
subtitle, I don't know,

00:32:07.400 --> 00:32:11.210 align:middle line:84%
but it's basically using a new
tuning system where every note

00:32:11.210 --> 00:32:15.500 align:middle line:84%
is divisible by nine, which is
the-- nine is the Pythagorean

00:32:15.500 --> 00:32:16.375 align:middle line:90%
number of stillness--

00:32:16.375 --> 00:32:17.220 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:32:17.220 --> 00:32:19.390 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: And the pi
ratio and all the things.

00:32:19.390 --> 00:32:19.600 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:32:19.600 --> 00:32:21.730 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: And so every
note is divisible by nine,

00:32:21.730 --> 00:32:29.880 align:middle line:84%
which makes the experience
be-- can I say deeply, deeply

00:32:29.880 --> 00:32:32.040 align:middle line:90%
catalytic of a stillness state.

00:32:32.040 --> 00:32:33.920 align:middle line:84%
And so I created
a 46-minute track

00:32:33.920 --> 00:32:36.660 align:middle line:84%
that's designed for, you
know, sessions, massages,

00:32:36.660 --> 00:32:38.430 align:middle line:84%
and deep healing
sessions that-- where you

00:32:38.430 --> 00:32:40.460 align:middle line:90%
let that music just infuse you.

00:32:40.460 --> 00:32:41.870 align:middle line:84%
And if you want
more information,

00:32:41.870 --> 00:32:43.200 align:middle line:90%
go to divine9music.com.

00:32:43.200 --> 00:32:44.300 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Divine 9, OK.

00:32:44.300 --> 00:32:45.370 align:middle line:90%
>>MALKIN: .com, yeah.

00:32:45.370 --> 00:32:46.110 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: All
right, divine9.com.

00:32:46.110 --> 00:32:48.200 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: You're asking me
all my favorite questions.

00:32:48.200 --> 00:32:49.241 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Well, I'm glad.

00:32:49.241 --> 00:32:51.820 align:middle line:84%
OK, I have just a couple
more before we wrap up.

00:32:51.820 --> 00:32:54.080 align:middle line:84%
And that has to do
with birthing someone

00:32:54.080 --> 00:32:57.150 align:middle line:84%
into the world and
that phase of music,

00:32:57.150 --> 00:32:59.020 align:middle line:84%
and then one that
you also work with,

00:32:59.020 --> 00:33:01.640 align:middle line:84%
which is music to
transition and help people

00:33:01.640 --> 00:33:06.170 align:middle line:84%
at end of life, which the boomer
generation who is now starting

00:33:06.170 --> 00:33:09.200 align:middle line:84%
to go through that process
isn't handling very well, being

00:33:09.200 --> 00:33:10.200 align:middle line:90%
the me generation.

00:33:10.200 --> 00:33:11.190 align:middle line:90%
>>MALKIN: Right.

00:33:11.190 --> 00:33:13.990 align:middle line:84%
Well you know, the
health care system

00:33:13.990 --> 00:33:16.470 align:middle line:84%
has done an extraordinary
job in dealing

00:33:16.470 --> 00:33:18.490 align:middle line:84%
with every other passage
except the end of life.

00:33:18.490 --> 00:33:19.290 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:33:19.290 --> 00:33:20.770 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: And
frankly-- I don't want

00:33:20.770 --> 00:33:23.311 align:middle line:84%
to be harsh, although there's
a lot of things that are coming

00:33:23.311 --> 00:33:25.800 align:middle line:84%
out with especially Atul
Gawande's book called "Being

00:33:25.800 --> 00:33:29.866 align:middle line:84%
Mortal," there is a lot
of new information coming

00:33:29.866 --> 00:33:31.240 align:middle line:84%
that really says
that we're still

00:33:31.240 --> 00:33:34.429 align:middle line:84%
in quite a barbaric
time around facing

00:33:34.429 --> 00:33:35.470 align:middle line:90%
eldering and end of life.

00:33:35.470 --> 00:33:36.270 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:33:36.270 --> 00:33:38.190 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: And how we
dispose of the elders

00:33:38.190 --> 00:33:40.660 align:middle line:84%
as trash, in a certain way,
and put them in nursing homes

00:33:40.660 --> 00:33:43.792 align:middle line:84%
and, you know, drug
them and all this.

00:33:43.792 --> 00:33:46.280 align:middle line:84%
This is my greatest passion
and my greatest commitment.

00:33:46.280 --> 00:33:50.130 align:middle line:84%
If I had a year to live, all I'd
do is focus on the end of life,

00:33:50.130 --> 00:33:53.232 align:middle line:84%
because its effect on everyone
in the culture is not just

00:33:53.232 --> 00:33:54.690 align:middle line:84%
for those who are
going through it,

00:33:54.690 --> 00:33:58.260 align:middle line:84%
but for all of us who are
watching and supporting

00:33:58.260 --> 00:34:01.960 align:middle line:84%
and loving the people we
love the most going through

00:34:01.960 --> 00:34:05.350 align:middle line:84%
unbelievable endless
interventions that undermine

00:34:05.350 --> 00:34:09.239 align:middle line:84%
the quality of life as they're--
what really needs to happen is

00:34:09.239 --> 00:34:12.230 align:middle line:84%
we need to acknowledge that
there's something called sacred

00:34:12.230 --> 00:34:15.870 align:middle line:84%
that isn't defined by a
religion but is defined

00:34:15.870 --> 00:34:19.770 align:middle line:84%
by an inclusivity that includes
religion but doesn't define it.

00:34:19.770 --> 00:34:25.750 align:middle line:84%
And music and the arts are the
perfect non-dogmatic catalyst

00:34:25.750 --> 00:34:28.120 align:middle line:84%
that doesn't bring an argument
about what faith are you

00:34:28.120 --> 00:34:30.949 align:middle line:84%
before you go and what, you
know, bring in last rites.

00:34:30.949 --> 00:34:33.900 align:middle line:84%
Let's make it sacred on
a universal level that

00:34:33.900 --> 00:34:37.530 align:middle line:84%
allows the beauty of
music to remind us

00:34:37.530 --> 00:34:42.969 align:middle line:84%
that we're hardwired to be able
to say, I love you, thank you,

00:34:42.969 --> 00:34:45.250 align:middle line:84%
I'm sorry, I forgive
you, goodbye,

00:34:45.250 --> 00:34:48.989 align:middle line:84%
in the famous words of the
five things that-- Ira Byock,

00:34:48.989 --> 00:34:53.570 align:middle line:84%
the famous doctor who-- so
we're hardwired to do that.

00:34:53.570 --> 00:34:55.270 align:middle line:84%
And what do we do
when we are actually

00:34:55.270 --> 00:34:56.730 align:middle line:90%
about to lose somebody?

00:34:56.730 --> 00:34:58.447 align:middle line:84%
Put them wires in,
do this intervention,

00:34:58.447 --> 00:35:01.030 align:middle line:84%
do this surgery no matter what
it's going to do to their life.

00:35:01.030 --> 00:35:02.520 align:middle line:90%
And it's an atrocity.

00:35:02.520 --> 00:35:05.130 align:middle line:84%
And we need to understand-- I'm
not saying that we don't need

00:35:05.130 --> 00:35:07.520 align:middle line:84%
to do something about it when
it's trying to save a life

00:35:07.520 --> 00:35:09.527 align:middle line:90%
if it's realistic, but--

00:35:09.527 --> 00:35:11.360 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: No, but what
you're speaking about

00:35:11.360 --> 00:35:15.190 align:middle line:84%
is almost gratuitous, and it
is barbaric in its own way,

00:35:15.190 --> 00:35:16.931 align:middle line:84%
what it puts that
person through.

00:35:16.931 --> 00:35:18.930 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: We're so hungry
to hold onto somebody,

00:35:18.930 --> 00:35:20.513 align:middle line:84%
but we don't know
that we're hardwired

00:35:20.513 --> 00:35:22.350 align:middle line:84%
to die the way we're
hardwired to be born.

00:35:22.350 --> 00:35:22.820 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Exactly.

00:35:22.820 --> 00:35:23.880 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: And so
when we're born,

00:35:23.880 --> 00:35:25.710 align:middle line:84%
the other thing that
is now troublesome

00:35:25.710 --> 00:35:27.480 align:middle line:90%
is the bonding process.

00:35:27.480 --> 00:35:29.570 align:middle line:84%
And the bonding-- new
studies have shown out

00:35:29.570 --> 00:35:33.580 align:middle line:84%
of Germany that are
mind-blowing-- what's his name?

00:35:33.580 --> 00:35:35.120 align:middle line:90%
Anyway, I forget his name.

00:35:35.120 --> 00:35:35.920 align:middle line:90%
Schroth?

00:35:35.920 --> 00:35:39.490 align:middle line:84%
He discovered a way of bonding
with the baby in the womb

00:35:39.490 --> 00:35:43.160 align:middle line:84%
through different practices in
music that actually has created

00:35:43.160 --> 00:35:45.324 align:middle line:84%
results so that the babies
sleep through the night,

00:35:45.324 --> 00:35:46.740 align:middle line:84%
they're less
collicky, and they're

00:35:46.740 --> 00:35:48.430 align:middle line:84%
more in this state
of all is well--

00:35:48.430 --> 00:35:49.680 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Makes perfect sense.

00:35:49.680 --> 00:35:51.150 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: --rather than the
shock into the world, right?

00:35:51.150 --> 00:35:53.140 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So are you
doing all is well movie--

00:35:53.140 --> 00:35:54.142 align:middle line:90%
music now for both the--

00:35:54.142 --> 00:35:55.850 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: For the
beginning and end, yes.

00:35:55.850 --> 00:35:56.460 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Beginning
and end of life?

00:35:56.460 --> 00:35:56.640 align:middle line:90%
>>MALKIN: Yes.

00:35:56.640 --> 00:35:57.473 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Wonderful.

00:35:57.473 --> 00:35:59.520 align:middle line:84%
Resonant Sounds,
or lisarafel.com.

00:35:59.520 --> 00:36:03.400 align:middle line:84%
We're doing actually a musical
called "Can You Hear Me Baby,"

00:36:03.400 --> 00:36:06.651 align:middle line:84%
which is songs and stories
about love, sex and OMG birth.

00:36:06.651 --> 00:36:07.650 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Oh, wonderful.

00:36:07.650 --> 00:36:09.774 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: And it's all
about basically like "Vagina

00:36:09.774 --> 00:36:11.670 align:middle line:84%
Monologues" on
pregnancy and birth--

00:36:11.670 --> 00:36:12.470 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:36:12.470 --> 00:36:14.553 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: And around the
choices that we can make.

00:36:14.553 --> 00:36:16.660 align:middle line:84%
Because again, the
doorways-- beginning

00:36:16.660 --> 00:36:19.810 align:middle line:84%
of life, end of life-- have
ramifications and ripples

00:36:19.810 --> 00:36:21.650 align:middle line:90%
that affect every part.

00:36:21.650 --> 00:36:26.060 align:middle line:84%
If we don't bond properly,
then that has ramifications

00:36:26.060 --> 00:36:28.520 align:middle line:84%
on the child's ability to
regulate and self-regulate

00:36:28.520 --> 00:36:30.420 align:middle line:84%
and deal with issues
of resilience--

00:36:30.420 --> 00:36:30.750 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Absolutely.

00:36:30.750 --> 00:36:32.458 align:middle line:10%
>>MALKIN: And a sense
of feeling like all

00:36:32.458 --> 00:36:34.070 align:middle line:10%
is well and like
you're not looking

00:36:34.070 --> 00:36:36.310 align:middle line:10%
through the world as an
enemy, but as a collaborator.

00:36:36.310 --> 00:36:39.129 align:middle line:10%
So music strategically
designed to do

00:36:39.129 --> 00:36:40.670 align:middle line:10%
that is something
that I've developed

00:36:40.670 --> 00:36:42.274 align:middle line:10%
with the "safe in
the Arms of Love--"

00:36:42.274 --> 00:36:43.190 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA: All is well.

00:36:43.190 --> 00:36:45.740 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: And all is
well at the end of life--

00:36:45.740 --> 00:36:48.190 align:middle line:84%
that experience of
dropping into trust,

00:36:48.190 --> 00:36:51.530 align:middle line:84%
as a child of a Jewish family
that has defined I suffer,

00:36:51.530 --> 00:36:52.330 align:middle line:90%
therefore I am--

00:36:52.330 --> 00:36:53.560 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:36:53.560 --> 00:36:55.500 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: --has been a
major issue in my life.

00:36:55.500 --> 00:36:57.730 align:middle line:84%
And I think, as
a wounded healer,

00:36:57.730 --> 00:37:00.840 align:middle line:84%
I've been looking
for ways to use music

00:37:00.840 --> 00:37:05.450 align:middle line:84%
that can be practical tools to
help us trust that, even when

00:37:05.450 --> 00:37:08.760 align:middle line:84%
we lose, even when things--
horrible things happen,

00:37:08.760 --> 00:37:11.384 align:middle line:84%
that there's a-- kind of
looking at it from, like,

00:37:11.384 --> 00:37:13.550 align:middle line:84%
if the angels looked at it,
if you believed in them.

00:37:13.550 --> 00:37:17.430 align:middle line:84%
Or looking at it from
a larger perspective,

00:37:17.430 --> 00:37:19.240 align:middle line:84%
we're not in control
of this, you know?

00:37:19.240 --> 00:37:19.580 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:37:19.580 --> 00:37:20.660 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: There's
something much larger

00:37:20.660 --> 00:37:22.830 align:middle line:84%
holding us all, whether
you believe in God or not.

00:37:22.830 --> 00:37:24.079 align:middle line:90%
There's something much larger.

00:37:24.079 --> 00:37:25.780 align:middle line:10%
And I think the
power of music is

00:37:25.780 --> 00:37:28.200 align:middle line:10%
it can wake us up
to that connection

00:37:28.200 --> 00:37:30.090 align:middle line:10%
to something much
larger than ourselves.

00:37:30.090 --> 00:37:30.385 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Absolutely.

00:37:30.385 --> 00:37:31.690 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: And that's
my goal in this life.

00:37:31.690 --> 00:37:33.023 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: I couldn't agree more.

00:37:33.023 --> 00:37:34.660 align:middle line:84%
You are here to help
relieve suffering

00:37:34.660 --> 00:37:37.337 align:middle line:84%
and to offer upliftment
through that frequency.

00:37:37.337 --> 00:37:38.170 align:middle line:90%
>>MALKIN: That's it.

00:37:38.170 --> 00:37:38.840 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: I appreciate that.

00:37:38.840 --> 00:37:40.881 align:middle line:84%
>>MALKIN: And the doorways
are one of the biggest

00:37:40.881 --> 00:37:41.720 align:middle line:90%
places we can do it.

00:37:41.720 --> 00:37:42.780 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

